00:05:41.090 --> 00:05:41.840
Wow.

00:05:41.840 --> 00:05:42.750
That's kind of bad.

00:05:42.750 --> 00:05:45.800
That's a global epidemic.

00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:48.590
3/4 of all people
would rather die.

00:05:48.590 --> 00:05:51.520
We're less afraid of dying than
we are of getting up on stage.

00:05:51.520 --> 00:05:55.510
So I want to let you
in on a little secret.

00:05:55.510 --> 00:06:00.860
It's actually fun to
present if we follow

00:06:00.860 --> 00:06:03.700
a couple of very,
very simple rules.

00:06:03.700 --> 00:06:05.240
The fear is real.

00:06:05.240 --> 00:06:07.110
We'll talk about it a
little bit later on.

00:06:07.110 --> 00:06:09.880
It's real, but it's
there for a good reason.

00:06:09.880 --> 00:06:11.420
The fear becomes
a problem when it

00:06:11.420 --> 00:06:14.330
gets so big that it
gets too crazy for us.

00:06:14.330 --> 00:06:15.872
But all the fear is
there to tell us,

00:06:15.872 --> 00:06:17.496
you're going to do
something stressful.

00:06:17.496 --> 00:06:18.300
You got to perform.

00:06:18.300 --> 00:06:20.210
If what we can do is
take that fear and say,

00:06:20.210 --> 00:06:21.660
hey, fear, I've seen you before.

00:06:21.660 --> 00:06:23.380
I know where you're coming from.

00:06:23.380 --> 00:06:27.600
I know your job to me is just to
make sure that I do a good job.

00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:29.730
We let the fear come in
and go right back out,

00:06:29.730 --> 00:06:31.530
and we use the energy
of it passing through

00:06:31.530 --> 00:06:33.180
to help us do a good job.

00:06:33.180 --> 00:06:34.860
And so what I want
to share with you

00:06:34.860 --> 00:06:38.040
is that when we give
a presentation-- it

00:06:38.040 --> 00:06:38.960
could be anything.

00:06:38.960 --> 00:06:41.570
It could be something that we're
just sharing with our team,

00:06:41.570 --> 00:06:44.000
or it could be a big
formal presentation

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:45.090
with a cast of thousands.

00:06:45.090 --> 00:06:46.260
It doesn't matter.

00:06:46.260 --> 00:06:48.220
The basic idea is
always the same.

00:06:48.220 --> 00:06:51.870
And it's kind of like
we are going on a trip.

00:06:51.870 --> 00:06:53.340
And here we are.

00:06:53.340 --> 00:06:55.480
This is us down here.

00:06:55.480 --> 00:06:58.060
And here is our idea,
the thing that we

00:06:58.060 --> 00:07:00.380
want to share in
our presentation.

00:07:00.380 --> 00:07:03.780
And usually what happens
is we take that thing

00:07:03.780 --> 00:07:04.910
and we show it to people.

00:07:04.910 --> 00:07:08.670
We say, this is my thing, this
is my idea, and here it is.

00:07:08.670 --> 00:07:13.260
And usually what happens is it's
not a very exciting engagement.

00:07:13.260 --> 00:07:16.390
It usually lies kind
of flat like this.

00:07:16.390 --> 00:07:18.442
And there we are sort
of showing our thing,

00:07:18.442 --> 00:07:19.900
and some people
are falling asleep,

00:07:19.900 --> 00:07:21.691
and some people are
checking their Android,

00:07:21.691 --> 00:07:23.420
and some people are
totally checked out.

00:07:23.420 --> 00:07:25.550
Well, you know what?

00:07:25.550 --> 00:07:27.870
I don't think we
should do that anymore.

00:07:27.870 --> 00:07:30.840
In fact, I think if there's
ever an opportunity for us

00:07:30.840 --> 00:07:33.000
to give a presentation
about anything that

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:35.660
has the likelihood of just lying
flat, we shouldn't give it.

00:07:35.660 --> 00:07:36.785
We should forget all about.

00:07:36.785 --> 00:07:39.750
Because, from now on, I think
it's really critical that we

00:07:39.750 --> 00:07:41.920
make every presentation
we give, no matter

00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:44.600
how low-key or
seemingly unimportant--

00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:48.110
we want to bend that lineup and
make every single presentation

00:07:48.110 --> 00:07:50.840
we give extraordinary.

00:07:50.840 --> 00:07:53.600
If it's not, why are
we giving it at all?

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:56.234
And what's the difference
between that flat line

00:07:56.234 --> 00:07:57.400
and that extraordinary line?

00:07:57.400 --> 00:07:58.990
It's a very, very simple thing.

00:07:58.990 --> 00:08:04.580
What is the difference
between this and this?

00:08:04.580 --> 00:08:07.300
A presentation it is
extraordinary-- it's

00:08:07.300 --> 00:08:07.850
very simple.

00:08:07.850 --> 00:08:11.590
It's one that changes people.

00:08:11.590 --> 00:08:14.160
And the change doesn't
need to be enormous.

00:08:14.160 --> 00:08:16.220
It could be a very small change.

00:08:16.220 --> 00:08:18.820
Or it could be
really, really huge.

00:08:18.820 --> 00:08:20.460
But what we want
to understand is

00:08:20.460 --> 00:08:23.450
that a presentation's
amazing, both for the audience

00:08:23.450 --> 00:08:27.260
and for us presenting it, when,
at some point during that 20

00:08:27.260 --> 00:08:29.820
minutes, 40 minutes, two
hours, whatever it is,

00:08:29.820 --> 00:08:32.362
somebody has a little
bit of a change.

00:08:32.362 --> 00:08:33.820
And that's what we
want to aim for.

00:08:33.820 --> 00:08:36.760
And in order to make that
happen, it's really simple.

00:08:36.760 --> 00:08:38.450
There are only three rules.

00:08:38.450 --> 00:08:40.820
Three really basic
rules for making

00:08:40.820 --> 00:08:43.320
an extraordinary presentation.

00:08:43.320 --> 00:08:45.970
And here they are.

00:08:45.970 --> 00:08:49.950
Rule number one, tell the truth.

00:08:49.950 --> 00:08:51.460
Wow.

00:08:51.460 --> 00:08:55.370
If we lead it with
the truth, the hearts

00:08:55.370 --> 00:08:58.520
of the people we're
talking with will follow.

00:08:58.520 --> 00:09:03.290
Rule number two, tell
that truth with a story.

00:09:03.290 --> 00:09:08.410
If we lead with a story,
understanding will follow.

00:09:08.410 --> 00:09:12.800
And rule number three, tell
that story with pictures.

00:09:12.800 --> 00:09:18.740
Because if we lead with the
eye, the mind will follow.

00:09:18.740 --> 00:09:21.470
Tell the truth, tell
it with a story,

00:09:21.470 --> 00:09:23.110
and tell that story
with pictures.

00:09:23.110 --> 00:09:25.480
And if we do that,
every presentation

00:09:25.480 --> 00:09:28.001
is going to be pretty amazing.

00:09:28.001 --> 00:09:29.750
We're going to go
through all three rules.

00:09:29.750 --> 00:09:31.970
And I want to start weirdly
with rule number three.

00:09:31.970 --> 00:09:34.830
I want to start with
the rule that says

00:09:34.830 --> 00:09:38.880
we tell our story with
pictures, because I want

00:09:38.880 --> 00:09:40.930
to share with you
initially some pictures.

00:09:40.930 --> 00:09:44.221
And we are actually going
to take a little test.

00:09:44.221 --> 00:09:45.220
It's a very simple test.

00:09:45.220 --> 00:09:46.480
I don't anyone to stress out.

00:09:46.480 --> 00:09:48.484
There's no passing or
failing in this test.

00:09:48.484 --> 00:09:49.900
All that's going
to happen is I am

00:09:49.900 --> 00:09:53.527
going to show you
30 random images.

00:09:53.527 --> 00:09:55.360
And I know they're
random, because all I did

00:09:55.360 --> 00:09:57.710
was go on Google Images
and download the first 30

00:09:57.710 --> 00:09:58.560
images that I saw.

00:09:58.560 --> 00:10:00.280
They're just 30 random images.

00:10:00.280 --> 00:10:01.530
I'm going to show them to you.

00:10:01.530 --> 00:10:03.000
We're going to look at them.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:04.910
The thing is, I
don't want you to try

00:10:04.910 --> 00:10:07.780
to memorize them or maybe
write down what they are.

00:10:07.780 --> 00:10:08.860
You won't have time.

00:10:08.860 --> 00:10:10.932
I just want you to look
at them, because we're

00:10:10.932 --> 00:10:12.140
going to go through each one.

00:10:12.140 --> 00:10:13.730
I'm going to give you about
a quarter of a second.

00:10:13.730 --> 00:10:15.313
We're just going to
go through really,

00:10:15.313 --> 00:10:17.140
really fast looking
at these images.

00:10:17.140 --> 00:10:20.490
So is everybody ready to
look at some pictures?

00:10:20.490 --> 00:10:20.990
All right.

00:10:20.990 --> 00:10:23.740
Up at the screen, we take
a breath, and here we go.

00:10:58.240 --> 00:10:59.530
OK.

00:10:59.530 --> 00:11:02.220
Can anybody tell us all 30
of those pictures in order?

00:11:02.220 --> 00:11:04.930
What did we just look at?

00:11:04.930 --> 00:11:05.900
Of course we can't.

00:11:05.900 --> 00:11:07.860
All right, so I want to
forget about that for moment.

00:11:07.860 --> 00:11:08.860
Remember there were three rules.

00:11:08.860 --> 00:11:10.040
I want to go to rule number one.

00:11:10.040 --> 00:11:12.170
Let's talk about rule number
one for a little well.

00:11:12.170 --> 00:11:15.370
Let's talk about this
idea of telling the truth.

00:11:15.370 --> 00:11:18.470
And my intention here is not
to go all Boy Scout on you

00:11:18.470 --> 00:11:20.550
and say, oh, it's all
about telling the truth.

00:11:20.550 --> 00:11:23.290
Here's the truth.

00:11:23.290 --> 00:11:28.040
A presentation looks like it's
about information sharing.

00:11:28.040 --> 00:11:30.000
That's what we think a
presentation is about,

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:31.790
and that is partially true.

00:11:31.790 --> 00:11:33.720
But in order for
information to be shared,

00:11:33.720 --> 00:11:35.950
something else has
to happen first.

00:11:35.950 --> 00:11:39.660
What a presentation is
really about is about trust.

00:11:39.660 --> 00:11:43.590
It is about me trying
to get you to trust me,

00:11:43.590 --> 00:11:48.640
and me trying to get me
to be trustworthy to do,

00:11:48.640 --> 00:11:51.130
and me trusting you back.

00:11:51.130 --> 00:11:52.850
The real idea is this.

00:11:52.850 --> 00:11:55.200
In order for there to be
any information exchange--

00:11:55.200 --> 00:11:59.420
if you don't trust me, if you
think I'm not very trustworthy,

00:11:59.420 --> 00:12:01.490
nothing good is going to happen.

00:12:01.490 --> 00:12:05.280
Here's kind of an interesting
part about this truth aspect.

00:12:05.280 --> 00:12:08.040
There is no faster
way to establish

00:12:08.040 --> 00:12:12.960
trust between ourselves than
for me to tell you the truth.

00:12:12.960 --> 00:12:14.940
We all have a kind
of a sixth sense.

00:12:14.940 --> 00:12:17.580
We know when someone
is BS-ing us.

00:12:17.580 --> 00:12:20.760
So the converse of this rule
is also true, that says this.

00:12:20.760 --> 00:12:25.910
There is no faster way to lose
our audience than to BS them.

00:12:25.910 --> 00:12:27.280
We can do it for a little while.

00:12:27.280 --> 00:12:29.630
But after a little bit
longer, people start to say,

00:12:29.630 --> 00:12:32.620
I don't think this
is really right.

00:12:32.620 --> 00:12:34.070
Now, OK, that's all fine.

00:12:34.070 --> 00:12:34.710
Tell the truth.

00:12:34.710 --> 00:12:39.880
But the tricky thing is
there is more than one truth.

00:12:39.880 --> 00:12:42.540
There are three truths.

00:12:42.540 --> 00:12:45.290
They all exist all the time.

00:12:45.290 --> 00:12:50.200
One of those truths is
the truth of the data.

00:12:50.200 --> 00:12:52.422
This is what the facts tell us.

00:12:52.422 --> 00:12:54.130
These are the things
that we can measure.

00:12:54.130 --> 00:12:55.588
These are the pieces
of information

00:12:55.588 --> 00:12:56.680
that we can collect.

00:12:56.680 --> 00:12:58.710
These are the facts, and
there is truth in them.

00:12:58.710 --> 00:13:00.400
They are true.

00:13:00.400 --> 00:13:03.240
There's a second truth,
though, isn't there?

00:13:03.240 --> 00:13:07.970
Which is the truth of, what do I
think about all of those facts?

00:13:07.970 --> 00:13:10.110
The truth that's in my head.

00:13:10.110 --> 00:13:12.470
And then there's a
third truth, which

00:13:12.470 --> 00:13:14.130
is the truth that's in my heart.

00:13:14.130 --> 00:13:19.234
What do I really believe
about all of these things?

00:13:19.234 --> 00:13:20.650
And what's
interesting, of course,

00:13:20.650 --> 00:13:23.660
is that very often these three
truths are not in alignment.

00:13:23.660 --> 00:13:25.270
They are not the same.

00:13:25.270 --> 00:13:29.970
I know we all have something
that we believe we know it

00:13:29.970 --> 00:13:34.890
in our heart to be true that the
data do not support or perhaps

00:13:34.890 --> 00:13:38.630
for which there are no data.

00:13:38.630 --> 00:13:40.760
What's interesting
about this, though,

00:13:40.760 --> 00:13:44.730
is that these truths are
all true all of the time.

00:13:44.730 --> 00:13:46.810
They all exist all of the time.

00:13:46.810 --> 00:13:49.590
And I wanted to give you
a little example right

00:13:49.590 --> 00:13:50.990
here about these truths.

00:13:50.990 --> 00:13:53.860
So what do we have here?

00:13:53.860 --> 00:13:56.030
I have a glass of water.

00:13:56.030 --> 00:13:59.307
Now, I can give you some facts
about this glass of water.

00:13:59.307 --> 00:14:01.140
And thank you,
[? Stephane ?], for providing

00:14:01.140 --> 00:14:03.570
this excellent prop.

00:14:03.570 --> 00:14:09.870
I can tell you that there are
about 4 cubic inches of H2O

00:14:09.870 --> 00:14:12.070
in this glass,
and I can tell you

00:14:12.070 --> 00:14:15.950
that there are 4 cubic
inches of oxygen and hydrogen

00:14:15.950 --> 00:14:17.090
in this glass.

00:14:17.090 --> 00:14:18.710
And those are the facts.

00:14:18.710 --> 00:14:20.480
That's great data.

00:14:20.480 --> 00:14:22.390
I can also say, what
do I think about that?

00:14:22.390 --> 00:14:25.800
Well, I know that metaphorically
a half-full, full-half empty

00:14:25.800 --> 00:14:28.350
glass is a sign of something.

00:14:28.350 --> 00:14:32.560
I know that many people think
that a half-full glass is

00:14:32.560 --> 00:14:35.090
a sign of optimism,
but half-empty glass

00:14:35.090 --> 00:14:36.480
is a sign of pessimism.

00:14:36.480 --> 00:14:39.950
So those are the things I
think about, those numbers.

00:14:39.950 --> 00:14:41.800
And then there's what I believe.

00:14:41.800 --> 00:14:45.630
I believe that this
glass is half full,

00:14:45.630 --> 00:14:48.590
and nothing anybody ever says
to me is going to change that.

00:14:48.590 --> 00:14:50.950
Those three truths are all
real and they all exist.

00:14:50.950 --> 00:14:54.650
And guess what's interesting
about those three truths,

00:14:54.650 --> 00:14:59.130
is it they are not
always the same.

00:14:59.130 --> 00:15:03.860
The way we perceive those
truths is very, very different.

00:15:03.860 --> 00:15:07.700
I like to represent it as
this kind of a pyramid.

00:15:07.700 --> 00:15:12.900
We have endless amounts
of factual truths.

00:15:12.900 --> 00:15:14.760
I mean, you're Google,
for goodness' sake.

00:15:14.760 --> 00:15:17.580
You collect more data
truths than anybody.

00:15:17.580 --> 00:15:19.550
We have more facts.

00:15:19.550 --> 00:15:20.970
The thing about
those data truths,

00:15:20.970 --> 00:15:23.020
though, those fact
truths, is that they're

00:15:23.020 --> 00:15:24.500
very easy to change.

00:15:24.500 --> 00:15:27.060
All that needs to happen is I
need to get a new data point.

00:15:27.060 --> 00:15:29.027
Today this might be a
fact, and tomorrow that

00:15:29.027 --> 00:15:29.860
might be a new fact.

00:15:29.860 --> 00:15:30.526
And that's fine.

00:15:30.526 --> 00:15:36.020
It's very easy to change
the truth of fact.

00:15:36.020 --> 00:15:38.337
The next truth that
sits on top of that

00:15:38.337 --> 00:15:40.670
that's a little bit harder
to change-- it's not the data

00:15:40.670 --> 00:15:42.240
itself, but what do
I think about it?

00:15:42.240 --> 00:15:45.200
What do I actually think
is the way the world is?

00:15:45.200 --> 00:15:47.210
Very difficult to change.

00:15:47.210 --> 00:15:48.990
I mean, if I think
things or something,

00:15:48.990 --> 00:15:52.070
it's going to take me a long
time to change the way I think.

00:15:52.070 --> 00:15:55.650
But the one that sits on the
top, the most difficult one

00:15:55.650 --> 00:15:58.830
of all to change, is the truth
of the heart-- the truths,

00:15:58.830 --> 00:16:00.880
the things that I believe.

00:16:00.880 --> 00:16:02.800
I don't care about
the damn data.

00:16:02.800 --> 00:16:05.370
I know this to be true.

00:16:05.370 --> 00:16:11.800
To change someone's beliefs
is extraordinarily difficult.

00:16:11.800 --> 00:16:14.870
But that is the truth
that really lasts.

00:16:14.870 --> 00:16:18.730
That is the change
that really matters.

00:16:18.730 --> 00:16:22.310
Point here, when we want to
change someone-- ourselves

00:16:22.310 --> 00:16:24.770
and our audience through
giving a presentation--

00:16:24.770 --> 00:16:27.120
we want to keep in mind
that we've got these three

00:16:27.120 --> 00:16:30.190
things that we're going
to be working through.

00:16:30.190 --> 00:16:34.840
How do we present these in a way
that makes sense to someone so

00:16:34.840 --> 00:16:37.194
that the level of
change takes place?

00:16:37.194 --> 00:16:39.110
Well, that brings us to
rule number two, which

00:16:39.110 --> 00:16:39.995
was telling a story.

00:16:42.920 --> 00:16:44.860
Why do we tell stories?

00:16:44.860 --> 00:16:47.470
Stories are the
expression of something

00:16:47.470 --> 00:16:49.740
we're going to call a storyline.

00:16:49.740 --> 00:16:52.170
Why are stories important?

00:16:52.170 --> 00:16:56.570
Well, because everything in
the world is complicated.

00:16:56.570 --> 00:16:57.680
Life is complicated.

00:16:57.680 --> 00:16:58.730
Problems are complicated.

00:16:58.730 --> 00:17:01.364
The truth is very complicated.

00:17:01.364 --> 00:17:02.780
And when something
is complicated,

00:17:02.780 --> 00:17:05.690
when something is complex,
it's almost impossible for us

00:17:05.690 --> 00:17:07.099
to figure out a
way to digest it.

00:17:07.099 --> 00:17:07.859
We don't want to.

00:17:07.859 --> 00:17:09.349
We just reject it.

00:17:09.349 --> 00:17:13.940
So what a storyline does is
it takes that complexity,

00:17:13.940 --> 00:17:18.069
and it forces it
into a line to make

00:17:18.069 --> 00:17:24.240
that complexity tolerable
enough for us to touch into it

00:17:24.240 --> 00:17:26.290
and try to experience
it long enough

00:17:26.290 --> 00:17:28.410
to try to make some
sense out of it.

00:17:28.410 --> 00:17:29.720
That's what a story does.

00:17:29.720 --> 00:17:32.240
It takes that
complexity and forces it

00:17:32.240 --> 00:17:35.820
into a line long enough for it
to began to make sense to us.

00:17:35.820 --> 00:17:38.550
That's all a story does.

00:17:38.550 --> 00:17:41.440
Which tells us that any
story, any presentation that's

00:17:41.440 --> 00:17:43.460
based on a story,
any presentation

00:17:43.460 --> 00:17:46.310
is going to be built
on a storyline.

00:17:46.310 --> 00:17:49.930
And that storyline
is always clear.

00:17:49.930 --> 00:17:52.350
There is a beginning,
there is an end,

00:17:52.350 --> 00:17:54.190
and there is
something that happens

00:17:54.190 --> 00:17:56.330
in between the two of them.

00:17:56.330 --> 00:18:01.980
The storyline is not endless,
the storyline is not confusing,

00:18:01.980 --> 00:18:04.740
and the storyline is not random.

00:18:04.740 --> 00:18:08.790
Whenever we're going to present
anything-- it doesn't matter

00:18:08.790 --> 00:18:10.510
whether it's a truth
of fact, it doesn't

00:18:10.510 --> 00:18:11.720
matter if it's a
truth of the head,

00:18:11.720 --> 00:18:13.803
or it doesn't matter if
it's a truth of the heart.

00:18:13.803 --> 00:18:15.520
When we're going to
present anything,

00:18:15.520 --> 00:18:18.600
we have to present it
in the form of a story,

00:18:18.600 --> 00:18:20.870
because that's the only
way understanding's

00:18:20.870 --> 00:18:23.030
going to come out of it.

00:18:23.030 --> 00:18:26.680
Because stories do two things.

00:18:26.680 --> 00:18:33.090
Certainly, they move us along
from a beginning to an ending.

00:18:33.090 --> 00:18:34.220
They have to do that.

00:18:34.220 --> 00:18:39.820
Come with me as I tell you about
public speaking or something.

00:18:39.820 --> 00:18:41.880
But they have to do a
second thing as well.

00:18:41.880 --> 00:18:44.800
It's not enough, as we know,
for the store to just lie there.

00:18:44.800 --> 00:18:48.230
The story also has
to me move us up.

00:18:48.230 --> 00:18:51.360
It has to change what you know
or what we understand or one

00:18:51.360 --> 00:18:52.890
of those truths.

00:18:52.890 --> 00:18:54.870
Otherwise, the story
has been ineffective.

00:18:57.570 --> 00:18:58.670
We talk about storylines.

00:18:58.670 --> 00:19:00.210
There are only four.

00:19:00.210 --> 00:19:03.330
There are only four
storylines in the world.

00:19:03.330 --> 00:19:05.140
Anytime give a
presentation, it is

00:19:05.140 --> 00:19:07.540
going to be based on one
of these four storylines.

00:19:07.540 --> 00:19:08.290
There are no more.

00:19:08.290 --> 00:19:09.620
There are only these four.

00:19:09.620 --> 00:19:11.440
And what I want to
do is map them out.

00:19:11.440 --> 00:19:14.690
How many people in here have
a piece of paper and a pen,

00:19:14.690 --> 00:19:17.690
actually have a piece
of paper and a pen?

00:19:17.690 --> 00:19:19.490
Because here's an
interesting aspect also

00:19:19.490 --> 00:19:22.720
about making a presentation.

00:19:22.720 --> 00:19:24.120
On a side note,
I've already been

00:19:24.120 --> 00:19:26.870
talking for about 15 minutes.

00:19:26.870 --> 00:19:29.600
And at this point, no
matter how charismatic I am,

00:19:29.600 --> 00:19:31.880
no matter how
compelling my story is,

00:19:31.880 --> 00:19:33.871
the human brain's going
to begin to check out.

00:19:33.871 --> 00:19:34.620
It doesn't matter.

00:19:34.620 --> 00:19:35.720
I could be singing and dancing.

00:19:35.720 --> 00:19:36.890
It's just going to happen.

00:19:36.890 --> 00:19:39.264
So one of the things that's
advisable at about this point

00:19:39.264 --> 00:19:41.820
in a presentation is give
the audience something to do.

00:19:41.820 --> 00:19:44.240
And give them something to
do that parallels what you're

00:19:44.240 --> 00:19:46.900
presenting about is often
a really nice little magic

00:19:46.900 --> 00:19:48.677
trick to re-engage
the brain again.

00:19:48.677 --> 00:19:50.510
So what we're going to
do is, rather than me

00:19:50.510 --> 00:19:54.300
telling you there are four
storylines and here they are,

00:19:54.300 --> 00:19:56.026
we are going to
make them together.

00:19:56.026 --> 00:19:57.900
So the way that we're
going to do this is I'd

00:19:57.900 --> 00:20:01.050
like you to take
your sheet of paper.

00:20:01.050 --> 00:20:02.830
I'm going to fake
it with this-- I'll

00:20:02.830 --> 00:20:05.180
use a horizontal Post-it note.

00:20:05.180 --> 00:20:08.410
I want you to imagine that
this is your sheet of paper.

00:20:08.410 --> 00:20:10.860
And hold it
horizontally like this.

00:20:10.860 --> 00:20:12.795
And what I want you to
do is fold it in half.

00:20:16.145 --> 00:20:17.770
Stephan, you're not
folding your paper.

00:20:20.440 --> 00:20:20.940
All right.

00:20:20.940 --> 00:20:22.380
Did everybody do that?

00:20:22.380 --> 00:20:24.570
Anybody need any help?

00:20:24.570 --> 00:20:26.484
OK, now what I want
you to do is we're

00:20:26.484 --> 00:20:27.650
going to fold one more time.

00:20:27.650 --> 00:20:32.090
I want you to fold it down
into quarters like that.

00:20:32.090 --> 00:20:33.440
All right.

00:20:33.440 --> 00:20:35.470
And now comes the big reveal.

00:20:35.470 --> 00:20:39.400
I want you to open it up and
admire this lovely handiwork it

00:20:39.400 --> 00:20:39.900
you've done.

00:20:39.900 --> 00:20:43.519
We've just created a perfect
four-quadrant little chart.

00:20:43.519 --> 00:20:46.060
And now we're going to draw,
for those of you who have a pen.

00:20:46.060 --> 00:20:48.101
The rest of you will have
to use your fingernail.

00:20:48.101 --> 00:20:49.310
We're going to draw.

00:20:49.310 --> 00:20:52.960
And what we're going to
draw, one in each quadrant,

00:20:52.960 --> 00:20:54.940
are the four storylines.

00:20:54.940 --> 00:20:56.440
So the first thing
we're going to do

00:20:56.440 --> 00:20:57.500
is we're going to
write some words.

00:20:57.500 --> 00:20:59.374
So what I'd like you to
do in quadrant number

00:20:59.374 --> 00:21:04.630
one right here is I'd like
you to write "report."

00:21:04.630 --> 00:21:06.150
In quadrant number
two, I'd like you

00:21:06.150 --> 00:21:11.110
to write "explanation."
"Explanation."

00:21:11.110 --> 00:21:16.120
In quadrant number three, I'd
like you to write "pitch."

00:21:16.120 --> 00:21:22.210
And in quadrant number four,
I'd like you to write "drama."

00:21:22.210 --> 00:21:25.680
These are the names
of the four storylines

00:21:25.680 --> 00:21:28.490
that define everything.

00:21:28.490 --> 00:21:30.620
Let's look at what they
actually look like, though.

00:21:30.620 --> 00:21:32.930
Because we know every storyline,
again, it starts at a point,

00:21:32.930 --> 00:21:34.990
and it moves along and
takes us somewhere else.

00:21:34.990 --> 00:21:36.240
So the report looks like this.

00:21:36.240 --> 00:21:37.360
I'd like you to
draw a little dot.

00:21:37.360 --> 00:21:37.980
We start here.

00:21:37.980 --> 00:21:40.760
And then draw flat line, and
make it look a little bit

00:21:40.760 --> 00:21:43.760
like an EEG, just little bursts
of information come along.

00:21:43.760 --> 00:21:46.920
But for the most part,
that report just lies flat.

00:21:46.920 --> 00:21:48.690
That's what a report does.

00:21:48.690 --> 00:21:49.820
I'm giving you some facts.

00:21:49.820 --> 00:21:50.330
Here's a fact.

00:21:50.330 --> 00:21:51.240
I'm giving you some more facts.

00:21:51.240 --> 00:21:51.740
Here's a fact.

00:21:51.740 --> 00:21:52.600
I'm giving you another fact.

00:21:52.600 --> 00:21:53.360
And then we're done.

00:21:53.360 --> 00:21:53.860
Thank you.

00:21:53.860 --> 00:21:54.600
Goodbye.

00:21:54.600 --> 00:21:55.640
All right.

00:21:55.640 --> 00:21:58.340
An explanation is a
little bit different.

00:21:58.340 --> 00:21:59.850
It starts down here.

00:21:59.850 --> 00:22:01.250
And I give you some information.

00:22:01.250 --> 00:22:03.380
And then we take a
step up together.

00:22:03.380 --> 00:22:05.580
And then we move along,
and we take another step.

00:22:05.580 --> 00:22:08.270
And we take another step,
and we take another step

00:22:08.270 --> 00:22:10.295
until we're at the end.

00:22:10.295 --> 00:22:12.420
Now, what's different about
this than the report is

00:22:12.420 --> 00:22:15.190
we can see that, rather than
just the line of facts, what

00:22:15.190 --> 00:22:17.690
we're actually doing
is building something.

00:22:17.690 --> 00:22:20.450
Each fact or each idea
builds on the previous one,

00:22:20.450 --> 00:22:23.500
so that by the time
we're done, we've

00:22:23.500 --> 00:22:27.180
had a change from this
level of understanding up

00:22:27.180 --> 00:22:29.470
to this new level
of understanding.

00:22:29.470 --> 00:22:30.960
We now have a new ability.

00:22:30.960 --> 00:22:33.260
We know something new.

00:22:33.260 --> 00:22:35.180
The pitch.

00:22:35.180 --> 00:22:37.200
We start here.

00:22:37.200 --> 00:22:39.060
And we've got a
bit of a problem.

00:22:39.060 --> 00:22:41.950
And that problem looks kind of
like a big old nasty mountain

00:22:41.950 --> 00:22:43.470
or a hurdle in front of us.

00:22:43.470 --> 00:22:46.080
And so what we're going to do
is we are going to jump over.

00:22:46.080 --> 00:22:48.080
We're going to throw
ourselves over that hurdle,

00:22:48.080 --> 00:22:50.220
and we're going to come
down on the other side.

00:22:50.220 --> 00:22:53.597
And what we will find is
that-- if we've done it well--

00:22:53.597 --> 00:22:55.430
we had to jump pretty
high, but we've still,

00:22:55.430 --> 00:22:56.890
even at the end after
we've come down,

00:22:56.890 --> 00:22:59.181
we're still at a higher
position than we were to start.

00:22:59.181 --> 00:23:00.700
That's a pitch.

00:23:00.700 --> 00:23:02.730
And the last one is the big one.

00:23:02.730 --> 00:23:05.910
This is called the drama,
where we start here,

00:23:05.910 --> 00:23:08.670
and everything is
just going along fine.

00:23:08.670 --> 00:23:10.960
And then all of a sudden,
the stuff hits the fan,

00:23:10.960 --> 00:23:13.350
and life starts to get bad,
and things get really bad.

00:23:13.350 --> 00:23:15.240
And then they get worse
and worse and worse

00:23:15.240 --> 00:23:18.910
until we're down here
in this pit of despair.

00:23:18.910 --> 00:23:20.480
It's all over.

00:23:20.480 --> 00:23:22.970
But no, we find a
way to come back.

00:23:22.970 --> 00:23:24.360
We start to work
our way back up.

00:23:24.360 --> 00:23:25.490
We figure out how to do it.

00:23:25.490 --> 00:23:26.340
We save ourselves.

00:23:26.340 --> 00:23:28.100
And we come back
with so much power

00:23:28.100 --> 00:23:32.060
that we actually burst
way past our starting line

00:23:32.060 --> 00:23:33.870
with this entirely
new lesson that we've

00:23:33.870 --> 00:23:37.280
learned because we
had to struggle.

00:23:37.280 --> 00:23:41.540
Every story, every presentation,
whatever we're going to give

00:23:41.540 --> 00:23:44.020
is going to be based on one
of those four storylines.

00:23:44.020 --> 00:23:47.570
Now, how would we
pick which storyline

00:23:47.570 --> 00:23:50.730
would be the best one for us
to use for our presentation?

00:23:50.730 --> 00:23:52.650
Well, there they are again.

00:23:52.650 --> 00:23:55.610
We might want to think about,
are we delivering information?

00:23:55.610 --> 00:23:59.110
If just information is enough,
then perhaps a report's enough.

00:23:59.110 --> 00:24:01.075
Do we want to deliver ability?

00:24:01.075 --> 00:24:02.950
Do we want to help people
have a new ability?

00:24:02.950 --> 00:24:05.080
We will use the explanation.

00:24:05.080 --> 00:24:08.720
Do we want to help people
get across a hurdle,

00:24:08.720 --> 00:24:10.450
solve a problem in a new way?

00:24:10.450 --> 00:24:12.080
Then we'd want to do a pitch.

00:24:12.080 --> 00:24:15.720
And do we want to have people
go through some suffering

00:24:15.720 --> 00:24:17.616
so that on the other
side they can increase

00:24:17.616 --> 00:24:18.990
their level of
happiness with us?

00:24:18.990 --> 00:24:21.020
Then we're going to
want to give the drama.

00:24:23.980 --> 00:24:26.780
A little bit earlier, I said
any extraordinary presentation

00:24:26.780 --> 00:24:27.540
changes people.

00:24:27.540 --> 00:24:29.690
Well, there are only four
ways that people change.

00:24:32.680 --> 00:24:34.250
We change our information.

00:24:34.250 --> 00:24:35.719
We know these things.

00:24:35.719 --> 00:24:38.010
Perhaps tomorrow, we're going
to know these new things.

00:24:38.010 --> 00:24:38.720
OK?

00:24:38.720 --> 00:24:40.450
We've changed our information.

00:24:40.450 --> 00:24:42.380
We can change our knowledge.

00:24:42.380 --> 00:24:44.170
What do we know?

00:24:44.170 --> 00:24:45.760
We may think this today.

00:24:45.760 --> 00:24:48.610
And tomorrow, perhaps
we'll know some new thing.

00:24:48.610 --> 00:24:50.640
We've changed our knowledge.

00:24:50.640 --> 00:24:52.460
We may change our action.

00:24:52.460 --> 00:24:55.170
Perhaps today, we're
just standing still.

00:24:55.170 --> 00:24:57.920
And tomorrow, we will be
running very, very fast.

00:24:57.920 --> 00:24:59.670
So we can change our action.

00:24:59.670 --> 00:25:03.030
Or the big one, of course, again
is we can change our beliefs.

00:25:03.030 --> 00:25:06.060
Perhaps today, we
are cat people.

00:25:06.060 --> 00:25:08.440
And maybe tomorrow, we are
going to be dog people.

00:25:08.440 --> 00:25:11.490
Ooh, wouldn't that be a change?

00:25:11.490 --> 00:25:13.570
Those are the only four
ways that people change.

00:25:13.570 --> 00:25:15.770
There's really not a
whole lot more than that.

00:25:15.770 --> 00:25:18.040
So here's the cool thing
about those four storylines.

00:25:18.040 --> 00:25:20.350
This is kind of the magic.

00:25:20.350 --> 00:25:25.730
If we know what kind of a change
we would like our audience

00:25:25.730 --> 00:25:28.340
to experience through
our presentation,

00:25:28.340 --> 00:25:31.270
we know which storyline to use.

00:25:31.270 --> 00:25:32.380
It's as simple as that.

00:25:32.380 --> 00:25:34.550
If we know what
kind of change we

00:25:34.550 --> 00:25:37.210
would like to have take place
during the presentation,

00:25:37.210 --> 00:25:39.800
we know what storyline to use.

00:25:39.800 --> 00:25:41.630
Like this.

00:25:41.630 --> 00:25:44.310
If I simply want to
change your information,

00:25:44.310 --> 00:25:48.000
I want to give you new facts,
I'm going to give you a report.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:50.669
If I want to change or
knowledge and your ability--

00:25:50.669 --> 00:25:52.210
if you can do this
today, but we want

00:25:52.210 --> 00:25:53.710
you to be able to
do that tomorrow--

00:25:53.710 --> 00:25:56.550
I'm going to give
you an explanation.

00:25:56.550 --> 00:25:59.590
If I want you to
change your actions--

00:25:59.590 --> 00:26:01.360
we are moving this
way today, but we

00:26:01.360 --> 00:26:05.760
need to move that way-- I am
going to give you a pitch.

00:26:05.760 --> 00:26:09.240
If we are going to
change our beliefs--

00:26:09.240 --> 00:26:12.130
we believe this
to be true, but I

00:26:12.130 --> 00:26:13.990
want you to believe
that to be true--

00:26:13.990 --> 00:26:19.530
the only way I can do that
is by giving you a drama.

00:26:19.530 --> 00:26:22.890
If I know which change I want
to have the audience experience,

00:26:22.890 --> 00:26:25.770
I know which storyline
I want to pick.

00:26:25.770 --> 00:26:28.650
Today, I want to focus on
just one of these storylines.

00:26:28.650 --> 00:26:31.770
It's the drama, because
this is really the big one.

00:26:31.770 --> 00:26:34.310
This is the one-- because
this changes beliefs,

00:26:34.310 --> 00:26:37.590
this is the one that
has the most power ever.

00:26:37.590 --> 00:26:39.510
And so I wanted to
spend time on this one.

00:26:39.510 --> 00:26:41.860
Yes, I'm guessing
that most of the time

00:26:41.860 --> 00:26:44.180
when at Google, you need
